05899nam a22009375i 9783110796858DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022939604  a97831107968587 a10.1515/97831107968582doi  a(DE-B1597)626286  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPA3015.S35bP64 2022 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a880.9223/eng/2022093000aPoikile Physis :bBiological Literature in Greek during the Roman Empire: Genres, Scopes, and Problems /ced. by Diego De Brasi, Francesco Fronterotta. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VI, 217 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aScience, Technology, and Medicine in Ancient Cultures ,x2194-976X ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPoikile Physis: A Short Introduction -- tA Question of Breeding? Aelian, Aristotle, And Alexander In India (NA 8.1) -- tAnimal Exemplarity in Imperial Greek Prose -- t“A Small Mirror of Greater and Nobler Enterprises” – Ants in Greek Imperial Literature -- tBiology Between Scientific Education and Ethical Paraenesis: The Physiologus -- tBiology and Theology: Zoological Systematics in Basil of Caesarea’s Hexaemeron -- tAelian’s Fabulous Trees -- tGalen as Phytotomist – His Study on the Fruit of Citrus Medica L. -- tA Hymn to Nature: Structure, Function, Design and Beauty in Galen’s Biology -- tBiological Metaphor and Cosmology The Rejection of Plato’s Artificialism by the Middle Platonists and Plotinus -- tBiology and Life in Plotinus’ Philosophy -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex locorum -- tIndex rerum -- tIndex codicum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBiological literature of the Roman imperial period remains somehow ‘underestimated’. It is even quite difficult to speak of biological literature for this period at all: biology (apart from medicine) did not represent, indeed, a specific ‘subgenre’ of scientific literature. Nevertheless, writings as disparate as Philo of Alexandria’s Alexander, Plutarch’s De sollertia animalium or Bruta ratione uti, Aelian’s De Natura Animalium, Oppian’s Halieutika, Pseudo-Oppian’s Kynegetika, and Basil of Caeserea’s Homilies on the Creation engage with zoological, anatomic, or botanical questions. Poikile Physis examines how such writings appropriate, adapt, classify, re-elaborate and present biological knowledge which originated within the previous, mainly Aristotelian, tradition. It offers a holistic approach to these works by considering their reception of scientific material, their literary as well as rhetorical aspects, and their interaction with different socio-cultural conditions. The result of an interdisciplinary discussion among scholars of Greek studies, philosophy and history of science, the volume provides an initial analysis of forms and functions of biological literature in the imperial period.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aBiological literaturezRome. 0aGreek literaturexHistory and criticism. 4aNaturwissenschaft. 4aPflanzen. 4aRhetorik. 4aTiere. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aanimals.  aplants.  arhetoric.  ascientific knowledge.1 aBerrens, Dominik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Brasi, Diego, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Brasi, Diego, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFronterotta, Francesco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFronterotta, Francesco, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFöllinger, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaars, Maximilian, econtributor.4ctb4htt